What is the projected market size & growth rate of the Life Science Instrumentation Market?

Analysis and Insights

Life Science Instrumentation : Global Life Science Instrumentation Market

Life science instrumentation market is expected to gain market growth in the forecast period of 2021 to 2028. Data Bridge Market Research analyses the market to account to USD 114.39 billion by 2028 and will grow at a CAGR of 7.35% in the above mentioned forecast period.

Life science instruments are largely used during the drug discovery for the analytical procedures and also during method validation. A lot of new technologies are used today for the drug development.

The increasing incidence of target infectious diseases and genetic disorders is amongst the important factors intensifying the growth and demand of life science instrumentation market. In addition, the high adoption of flow cytometry techniques in research and academia and growing outsourcing of sterilization services are also contributing to the growth in the global market over the forecast period of 2021 to 2028. Also the declining costs of genome sequencing as well as rising use of capillary electrophoresis with mass spectroscopy are also enhancing the growth of the market. Furthermore, the increasing incidence of hospital-acquired infections and rapid advancements in NGS platforms are also one of the significant factors fueling the growth of the life science instrumentation market. Increasing investments in pharmaceutical R&D will make sure high industry growth over the forecast period.

The growing demand for analytical instruments, high growth of the pharmaceutical and biotechnology industries and widening application scope of analytical instruments are offering significant growth opportunities for the market in the forecast period of 2021 to 2028.

However, the high cost of instruments, lack of skilled professionals along with technical limitations related with qPCR and dPCR techniques and high cost of advanced microscopes will curb the growth of the life science instrumentation market, whereas the insufficient infrastructure for research in emerging countries and pricing pressure has the potential to challenge the growth of the life science instrumentation market.

